revisions.rev:
[[File:2008 LPGA Championship - Annika Sorenstam tee shot.jpg|thumb|right|upright|200px|alt=A blonde-haired woman in a pink shirt and hat with white pants and glove and a driver in her hand in the position at the end of a golf swing|[[Annika SÃ¶renstam]] was a three-time winner of the event in 1995, 1996 and 2006, and one of seven golfers to repeat as champion.]]
The [[United States Women's Open Championship (golf)|U.S. Women's Open]] is an annual [[golf]] competition that was established in 1946.<ref name=USOPEN>{{cite web|url=http://lpga.com/content/USWomensOpenSummary.pdf |title=U.S. Women's Open |publisher=[[LPGA Tour]] |accessdate=2010-06-25 |format=PDF }}</ref> As of 1953, the championship is sanctioned by the [[United States Golf Association]] (USGA), which is the governing body of the game in the [[United States]].<ref name=TROPHY>{{cite web |url=http://www.usgamuseum.com/exhibits_artifacts/usga_trophies.aspx |title=USGA Trophies |publisher=[[United States Golf Association]] Museum |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> Previously, the event was played as the "Ladies" Open, and was sanctioned by the Women's Professional Golfers Association from 1946â1948.<ref name=TROPHY /> In addition, the [[LPGA]] (Ladies Professional Golf Association) sanctioned this tournament from 1949â1952.<ref name=TROPHY /> This event is one of the four [[Women's major golf championships|women's major championships]].<ref name=USOPEN /> The other major championships are the [[Kraft Nabisco Championship]], the [[LPGA Championship]], and the [[Women's British Open]].<ref name=MAJORS>{{cite web|url=http://lpga.com/tournament_majors.aspx?mid=1&pid=38|title=Tournaments-The Majors|publisher=LPGA Tour|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> This event has always been played in [[stroke play]] with the exception of the first competition in 1946, and is currently the third women's major of the year.<ref name=MAJORS />  

The first trophy presented to the champions was from the Spokane Athletic Round Table, until 1953.<ref name=TROPHY /> The original trophy by the USGA was designed by the [[silversmith]] of J. E. Caldwell and Co. of Philadelphia.<ref name=TROPHY />  This trophy was first presented to the champion in 1953, when [[Betsy Rawls]] won, and was retired to the USGA Museum in 1992.<ref name=TROPHY />  Now, the champion receives the Harton S. Semple trophy, named for a former USGA Committeeman and the USGA President from 1973â1974.<ref name=TROPHY />  His family and friends commissioned a replacement replica trophy in July 1992.<ref name=TROPHY />  The first winner to receive it was [[Patty Sheehan]] in 1992.<ref name=TROPHY />

Rawls and [[Mickey Wright]] hold the record for the most victories with four.<ref name=USOPEN />  The most consecutive wins at the event is two by Wright, [[Susie Berning]], [[Hollis Stacy]], [[Annika SÃ¶renstam]], [[Donna Caponi]], [[Betsy King]] and [[Karrie Webb]].<ref name=USOPEN />  The lowest{{ref label|Par|a|a}} winning score for 72 holes in relation to [[Par (score)|par]] is 16-under by [[Juli Inkster]] in 1999.<ref name=USOPEN /> The lowest aggregate winning score for 72 holes is 272 by SÃ¶renstam in 1996 and Inkster in 1999.<ref name=USOPEN /> Conversely, the highest winning score for 72 holes in relation to par is 13-over by [[Murle Lindstrom]] in 1962.<ref name=USOPEN /> The highest aggregate winning score for 72 holes is 302 by Rawls in 1953 and [[Kathy Cornelius]] in 1956, and they won both events in playoffs.<ref name=USOPEN /> The oldest champion was [[Babe Zaharias]] in 1954, when she was 43 years 0 months and 6 days old.<ref name=USOPEN2>{{cite web|url=http://www.usga.org/uploadedFiles/USGAHome/press_room/media_guide/05WomensOpen%281%29.pdf |title=2010 U.S. Women's Open media guide |publisher=[[United States Golf Association]] |accessdate=2010-03-24 |format=PDF }}</ref> The youngest champion was [[Inbee Park]] in 2008, when she was 19 years 11 months and 17 days old.<ref name=USOPEN2 /> The U.S. Women's Open has had eight wire-to-wire champions, which are the following: Zaharias in 1954, [[Fay Crocker]] in 1955, Wright in 1958, [[Mary Mills (golfer)|Mary Mills]] in 1963, [[Catherine Lacoste]] in 1967, Berning in 1968, [[Donna Caponi]] in 1970, and [[JoAnne Carner]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lpgamediacenter.com/(S(mal14a455fezhkutr3anjyjb))/Printweb.aspx?Page=Major%20records%2C%20all&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Major records, all|publisher=LPGA Media Center|accessdate=2011-06-23}}</ref> The current champion is [[So Yeon Ryu]].

